bio:
I have been the proverbial Jack-of-All-Trades / Master-of-None for most of my adult life. I've been tearing things apart to see how they work since I discovered my father's Dewalt Power Drill back when I was 8. I've dabbled my feet into everything from car mechanics, to computer networking, and everything in-between. My chosen career is repairing medical equipment, and I now spend most of my days repairing and maintaining MRI and CT scanners (although I started my career on beds and infusion pumps).

I have ADHD, and so I always have at least 6 projects in some form of completion (Sometimes I even get them done!!!). I just purchased a 3D Printer to find another thing to dabble in, and just realized that I could build a bigger and better one simply by tinkering as I always do. So that got added to my ever-expanding list of projects in progress.

I am by no means the most intelligent person in the world, but I learn quickly and like to pass on what I've gleaned from experience (Remember kiddies! Exploding things are a learning opportunity!), and will continue to do so here as well!

I'm pretty new to modern 3D design software so my first designs probably won't be spectacular. I took AutoCad for digital circuit design in college way back in 1992 and wow have things changed for the better. I'm a lot better at designing things for laser cutting, though. I've been using Corel Draw for years and the concept of designing flat things that assemble into 3D things has been easy to learn, much easier than making models in 3D. But learning new things is part of the fun, right?

Modifying my machines has been as fun as creating things. My Laser cutter now has a 1000mm 45w tube and a Cloudray power supply. It also has LED lighting and a high powered, adjustable exhaust fan. It cuts 1/4" hickory with ease and 3mm plywood and MDF cut like butter. My Tronxy 3D printer now has a Y carriage that I designed and laser cut.

With the Additive Manufacturing Certificate from SME, America Makes, and MSOE as well as many years of engineering experience in product development, plastic part design, plastic part failure analysis, composite materials, composites manufacturing, resin casting, metal fabrication, and wood working we have plenty of expertise to assist you with your rapid prototyping needs. Furthermore, we are ready to help you take your project from start to completion with over 10 years of CAD (SolidWorks, ProE, Fusion 360, AutoCAD) experience. These softwares also allow us to perform FEA (finite element analysis).

We have two rapid prototyping processes in-house; FDM and SLA. FDM projects are serviced by a Stratasys DImension and the SLA projects are serviced by a Fromlabs Form 2.

Our FDM machine makes use of real engineering thermoplastics; currently ABS and ABS/PC alloy materials. The 8x8x12" build envelope is house in a controlled environment chamber. The additional heat of the environment and high nozzle temperature allows for high quality parts in terms of precision, accuracy, and mechanical properties. We have completed projects that included parts of LEGO size up through large robot housing parts.

Our SLA (Stereo Lithography Apparatus) creates beautiful parts in liquid thermoset plastic resins. With its precision laser system this process is capable of producing parts with 25 micron (0.001") layers (Z) and even better X/Y precision. The minimum feature size for this process is about 0.003". Because of this it is often used to produce investments for jewelry production. The process is also excellent for producing parts that simulate ABS thermoplastic in a highly precise manner. We offer the full range of Formlabs resins which include general purpose grey, presentation-ready white, high precision black, Tough (ABS simulation), clear (great for working with light or showcasing internal features), Castable (for investment casting jewelry or other metals), and Flexible (a material that is great for simulating over-molds).

Please send us a message and check seek out our online portfolio. We will be more than happy to provide a comprehensive set of options to see your project through to its full capacity. We are happy to provide robust quotes to help you make the best decision for your situation and your parts as fast as possible! Rapid for fast, 1 for first!

If your project requirements fall outside of our services or capabilities, please feel free to contact us for a recommendation. With an extensive network of vendors ranging from injection molding, CNC machining, CNC routering, laser cutting, metal fabrication, painting, materials manufacturers, and large scale engineering we can help find a vendor for you!
